            <table border='0'>  <tr>    <td class='ind'><img src="s.gif" height="1" width="0"></td><td valign="top" class="votelinks"><center><a id='up_14336570' href='vote?id=14336570&amp;how=up&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D14335513'><div class='votearrow' title='upvote'></div></a></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px;"><span class="comhead">
          <a href="user?id=zokier" class="hnuser">zokier</a> <span class="age"><a href="item?id=14336570">3 hours ago</a></span> <span id="unv_14336570"></span><span class="par"></span> <a class="togg" n="5" href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="return toggle(event, 14336570)"></a>          <span class='storyon'></span>
                  </span></div><br><div class="comment">
                  <span class="c00">I don&#x27;t quite understand how WannaCry became such a big deal. Ransomware is already old thing, SMB worms even older. WannaCry didn&#x27;t even use a 0day ffs, the patch for this was already published few months ago (and not particularly quietly I might add). There is very little novel about WannaCry as far as I can tell. Additionally W10 apparently was not vulnerable in the first place.<p>All this, and still WannaCry hit the main evening news, which at least around here is somewhat high bar. Not sure what to think about that.<span>
              </span><div class='reply'>        <p><font size="1">
                      <u><a href="reply?id=14336570&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D14335513%2314336570">reply</a></u>
